text: It's sad Marvel couldn't stay true to that comics due to character and plot constraints brought about them not owning all of their characters. They had to use Bucky here where he shouldn't have been. The real reason behind it is more political.  Due to the increasing numbers of B-list heroes who have been blatantly failing in saving people, the government issued a mandate that all past, present and future "inhumans/Enhanceds" must be registered and be screened fit to to be a hero with it they also have to surrender their secret identities. Capt. America saw this as a liability rather than a fix. What if the enemy managed to hack said registry and used all that info against the heroes. He opposed the mandate backed up by the Avengers and affiliated heroes  Iron Man and Ant-man saw this a sign of stability. They were tired of B-list heroes left unchecked who more bad than good and they also saw earth-foreign entities as a liability and could not be fully trusted.  What they wanted was a sense of order that could help everyday citizens rather than wannabe heroes running amok.   All in all, Cant wait for this! whoo!

text: I went to see Winter Soldier expecting to be bored or at least disdainful of another lame, excremental Hollywood comic-book-to-screen offering.¬†¬†But I went back and saw it again the following week.¬† Winter Soldier¬†wasn't¬†just some good special effects and pretty damn awesome action sequences. Chris Evans' performance powerfully¬†breathes life into a persona that could easily be as dry and flat as the movie characters in old 1940s movies, the era from which Captain America originally came. That he can stand equally and¬†visibly among more eye catching heroes like Thor, the Hulk and Robert Downey Jr.'s Iron Man is a strong testament to Evens' ability as an actor¬†in his role as Captain America, a role in which no one will ever be able to replace him.¬† That being said, going by the clip above and the return of the Russo Bros. as dual directors of Civil War, I do look forward to seeing it.

text: This movie couldn't be any more similar to Dawn of Justice yet bet so different at the same time.  Dawn of Justice is going to be big, and rightfully so- after all, Superman's battle against Zod and his followers was seen around the world.  The motivations of the respective sides are fittingly grandiose:  Superman: "I'm just here to help, but I think this Bat-man vigilante is going to get in the way of that." Batman: "This alien has too much power. He needs to be stopped."  As a result, Superman is going to be targeting Batman (as Clark Kent) as much as Batman will be targeting Superman.  For Civil War, however, it's a much more personal affair. Steve is only doing what he's doing because he knows that Bucky's crimes as the Winter Soldier are immense. Bucky might even be executed, and since he's the only thing Steve has to his old life, no one will be taking Bucky from him again anytime soon.  Who knows? Steve might even agree, to some extent, with Tony Stark on this one.

text: This is a civil war regarding whether the superheroes would agree or disagree with the government forcing them to register. Brains and muscles are nothing about what goes on. Justice and heroism are everything.
author: Captain Marvel Wilson

text: Here is why these two heroes are leading different factions of Avengers. Iron Man believes that being unregulated could be dangerous for everyone around him although he and his fellow Avengers have worked hard together to save people before. Captain America believes that registering for government service will go against the morals that heroes stood for as well as realising that the government could end up following a corrupt system that will result in the deaths of many people worldwide. The hero who I believe is right is Captain America. He will always be my favourite Marvel superhero from now on.

text: For anyone here who is new to the MCU and wants to watch this movie here is the List of the Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU) films in order of release:  PHASE 1: Iron Man (2008) The Incredible HULK (2008) Iron Man 2 (2010) THOR (2011) Captain America: The First Avenger (2011) The Avengers (2012)  PHASE 2: Iron Man 3 (2013) THOR: The Dark World (2013) Captain America: The Winter Soldier (2014) Guardians Of The Galaxy (2014) Avengers: Age of Ultron (2015) Ant-Man (2015)  Those are ALL, watch them in that order, and get ready for Phase 3 which is the FINAL, and Last phase of the MCU.  PHASE 3: Captain America: CIVIL WAR (2016) Doctor Strange (2016) Guardians Of The Galaxy Vol. 2 (2017) Untitled Spider-Man film (2017) THOR: Ragnarok (2017) Black Panther (2018) Avengers: Infinity War- Part 1 (2018) Ant-Man and the Wasp (2018) Captain Marvel (2019) Avengers: Infinity War- Part 2 (2019) Inhumans (2019)

text: In the aftermath of Civil War, Captain America is taken into S.H.I.E.L.D. custody where he is assassinated per the order of the Red Skull. Crossbones snipes at him while Sharon Carter, who has been brainwashed by Doctor Faustus, (and Cap's girlfriend) posing as a S.H.I.E.L.D. psychiatrist, delivers the killing shot. S.H.I.E.L.D. director Tony Stark and Black Widow hunt Captain America's murderers. Falcon, Captain America's old partner, follows his own leads to find the killers. Meanwhile, Bucky Barnes decides to kill Tony Stark, blaming him for Captain America's death.

text: Why is there a fight over this? It was well established that Bucky was brainwashed into doing everything he was doing. With how he now remembers¬†who he was, why is he still being accused of his crimes? Or at least why is he being denied his fair trial at the least? Their just storming through trying to kill the poor guy. He fought long and hard for his country, then as he stated, he fought extremely hard for Captain America, who fought extremely hard for his country. Then he gets captured and brainwashed into becoming Hydra's puppet for how many years? 60? 80? (its late at night I don't remember how long exactly right now.) and all the while his friends and family die of old age. he wakes back up in the 21 century having lost everyone but his¬†best friend and finding out he was made to kill so many people, the guy is in a terrible state¬†he¬†doesn't deserve a kill order on his head.¬†At the very least he should have gotten a fair trial to defend himself. He wasn't given that at all. Then theres¬†the government trying to pull down the avengers to their beck and call. Being called evil for doing whats right. text: OK OK let me break this all down, Imma go all nerdy on y‚Äôall.   First off, Ignoring the teams for now lets focus on Cap and Iron man.   Cap: Has little no no upgrades to his overall gear and strengths in close counters combat fighting (This is why all the #TeamIronMan is nervous at the end of the trailer). Cap also has a shield with a seriously strong medal.   Iron Man:  Has a new suit, witch If I assume correctly, is the Model 38 Bleeding edge Armor (Not as known because it came before the Iron destroyer armor). text: I wanted to see secretary Ross more in the MCU. In the Incredible Hulk he was clearly an antagonist. But his presence in this movie, stated that he had changed. He was just the face of the UN, and the 117 countries that signed to keep the avengers under control. Since he had a history with the hulk I think thats why he was the man to come with the accords. I dont agree with everything the accords stand for, but I was totally on team Iron Man in Civil War. Their destructions and casaulties was too much. They couldnt just roll in every country without legal justice to do so. Cap didnt agree with anything. His honor was too high as well as his ego. And when you see how the "government have supervision of the superheroes" was in the later movies especially Homecoming it is no doubt that Iron Man had right. "If we can`t accept limitations, were not better than the bad guys"
